            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                We thought, “Well, if we're called, I guess we'd go again.” <br /><br /> 

                So she said, “Would you come to England?” <br /><br /> 

                I said, “Well, I don't know. I guess we would!” <br /><br /> 

                She said, “Our mission president over here said if you would come, he would see that you receive a call to come to England. They need couple missionaries in his mission.” <br /><br /> 

                I talked it over with Kenneth and we decided yes. We would serve another mission happily. So the paperwork was done, and before very long our call came in the mail, and we were called to serve for eighteen months in the England Leeds Mission. We were excited! We were excited especially to go to England, because that's where our daughter and her family lived. It was a wonderful mission. We enjoyed it, we learned a lot, and we had a very special experience over there. 


            </span>
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory5-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory5');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory5" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    We were quite close and spent much time together but I had reservations about feelings for Ken and after a few weeks of dating I pretty well made the decision to return to Seattle to renew a relationship I had left when I came home after graduation. <br /><br />

                    When I told Ken what I was about to do he said, “Well, I will just have to come up there after you because the Lord has let me know you are to be my wife.”  <br /><br />

                    Well, that set me back a bit and after much pondering for awhile decided that I had better give the relationship a bit more time. So I stayed with employment at the doctor's office and continued seeing Ken and not much longer after that we became engaged. Ken put an engagement ring on my finger in that darn green pickup before we went into the stake dance and we were promised to each other.  <br /><br />

                    Had Ken not been there I would surely have made a serious mistake and married the wrong person. Whether Ken’s coming home early from his mission had anything or not to do with how it all turned out we will never really know for sure in this world, but one thing that is for sure, we feel we were guided by the Spirit of our Heavenly Father in our relationship and I am very grateful to know that he helped me to make the right decision about my future. As I look back at it all now I can see the mistake I would have made but at the time it was difficult to rationalize correctly because emotions were in control and it is difficult at times to separate the true, lasting feelings from superficial, emotional responses. <br /><br />

                    We were married in the Idaho Falls temple by John R. Sayer on the 21st of September. The temple was closed for maintenance at that time, so Ken and Uncle Jack took me to the Salt Lake temple to receive my endowment. I was alone with no one to be by my side and it was a very difficult experience for me. My parents were not active in the church at all and no one else was able to go through the temple with me. How different now when many family members support one who is attending for the first time. Later as I served a mission in the Mexico City temple and observed the quiet kindness and attention given to a “primera ves” which is a first endowment I no longer wonder at the nervousness I felt at being alone for what should have been a very spiritual and special experience. The Idaho Falls Temple was actually closed for renovation, but we were able to be married on Sept 21st when it was opened for sealings. A lasting memory. <br /><br />

                    Ken’s Aunt Grace and Aunt Mary made our temple clothing for us so we would have our own right from the first which has been a blessing and inspiration to us all our married life. We have also seen that each of our children have their own complete set of temple clothing when they got married. We hoped the example would carry all through each of their own families and help them to go to the temple frequently. <br /><br />

                    We stopped along the way back home to pick fruit..peaches, etc. to take home to can for our very first food supply. We stayed in a motel somewhere that night because I was so tired and worn completely out after the emotional experiences of that day. Actually the whole experience was not very pleasant to me because I was alone without any help in the temple from family. <br /><br />

                    Our wedding day was a beautiful blue day with lots of sunshine and we had our families with us and it was a lovely day. My wedding dress was a beautiful, ivory satin with a bustle! I loved it and it was and still is a treasure to me. The evening of our wedding we had a reception at Ken’s home and it was very nice. Not too many attended because of my parents’ inactivity in the church and Ken’s family had just moved into their ward in Idaho Falls from the Milo farm but we had much family and it was a beautiful evening. Our wedding cake was designed as near as possible to the I.F. temple. Donna Rasmussen (Cook) and Lois Bacon Packer were my bridesmaids and Leo Avery was Ken’s best man, however, he didn’t show up until way too late so my brother Bart stood with Ken. <br /><br />

                    When it was time to get changed and leave for our honeymoon we had quite a time eluding the “shivaree-ers” and not until many years later did I learn that my Dad had been the chief instigator of the goings-on after the reception! <br /><br />

                    We finally made our escape in Ken’s parents car that we used for our honeymoon travel and spent our first married night in the Colonial Motel in Blackfoot. We then drove on to southern Utah and the parks there and then on to California for our 10 day honeymoon. Not too many photos of that trip…cameras at that day and age were not common for everyone. <br /><br />

                    When we returned from our honeymoon we moved into an apt on J Street in Idaho Falls. A one bedroom apartment with nothing else but a small kitchen at one end with the bedroom at the other end of a short hall and the bathroom in between…the problem being that when we moved in we didn’t know that the bathroom had to be shared with another apartment, so we had to keep the hall door open all the time; the door was between the kitchen and the bedroom, so it was mighty inconvenient and not private at all. We lived there for about a month and then moved out and into another apartment on Elm Street on the 2nd floor but it was nice and it was all ours! We had a private bathroom! I remember that apartment very well…I remember the night that Harry Truman won the presidency even though it had been put in headlines in the papers all over the country that Thomas Dewey had won. I was standing at the ironing board when we heard the news over the radio. <br /><br />
