            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            
               The work out there was challenging. It was quite an assignment for Kenneth and I. Kenneth had served in the bishopric in one of the wards that we lived in, but to be called to organize a branch of the Church, get it established, and gather up the members was quite a challenge. We did quite a bit of traveling. We wondered, “Is this something that we can do?” We knew that we needed to depend on the Lord totally. To be able to do this was going to require a lot of faith and being dependent on the Lord.
 
            </span>
            
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Though we felt like we were lacking in experience, we also felt that if we were prayerful and trusted in the Lord to help us, then we could do it. And we began to do the work that we needed to do out there. One of the sister missionaries shared a thought, and it helped me a great deal. That thought was, “Whom the Lord calls, He qualifies.” I took that to heart. It helped me understand that we could just go ahead and do what needed to be done the best that we could do it. So we did. <br /><br /> 

                    We began to gather up the members, and the members were so happy to have a branch organized in their area again. We had good support from those that we could find. We were given a computer print-out with dozens and dozens of names on it of people that were living there and supposedly members. Most of them were inactive. To be able to go into that area and gather up inactive members and encourage them to come back and be part of the Church again was quite a challenge. But it was rewarding. It strengthened our testimonies. It helped us to have faith in what we could do with the Lord's help. <br /><br />

                    We had help from Elders and Sisters, wonderful young missionaries who were out in that mission. Working together we were able to get the branch started, and it flourished. When we left that mission, we had about thirty or forty people coming to church regularly. That was good. We were happy that we had been given that assignment and happy to be able to do the work there and feel that was what the Lord wanted us to do. We were happy to do it.
