            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                So three years after Kenneth passed, Bishop Olaveson and I finally got together with all the mission possibilities. He wanted me to go and felt it was right but I didn't know if it was right for about a year. Being with Ruby was so important for me but yet in my heart I knew that a mission was what I needed to do. I was not sure if I really wanted to serve another mission, yet feeling I needed to be serving in the church more than I was. 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory4-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory4');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory4" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    So after spending one more winter in Arizona with my brothers and sisters I filled the papers and sent them off to Salt Lake hoping that of all the places in the world that the Lord could and would send me it wouldn't be in another Spanish speaking mission. When all was done, the papers were sent in and I had courage enough to tell Ruby, the waiting process began and I knew that once more this was “for real.” The wait for the call to arrive was about three weeks and on the day the letter arrived the suspense was almost palatable. <br /><br />

                    Living in Rigby has a few advantages that those who live in the “big cities” don't have. The post office folks knew that I was waiting for a call so on the day it was to arrive, and it didn't appear in my mail box, the dreaded wait was extended for a few more hours, the mission papers came in later in the day at the post office so when they arrived the post office folks called my home and Shawn went over to pick them up, called Marlon. Marian. And Taylor then presented the letters to me. And there it was, the temple in Mexico City. My very first thought when I saw the words was, “The temple, thank goodness it is for the temple.” <br /><br />

                    I have to admit that was some disappointment there, and there for some time. Why was the Lord sending me to the very place I had set my heart on that I did not want to go? Had I been counseling the Lord all that time when I knew that I shouldn’t be? Some of my most favorite scriptures are in the book of Jacob in the Book of Mormon, especially this verse: “Seek not to counsel the Lord, but to take counsel from his hand” (Jacob 4:10). This scripture took on a whole new meaning for me. I was troubled for quite some time about the call. I knew I would accept the call but my heart was not not involved, until one morning while reading the Book of Mormon in Spanish. I came upon another scripture that is a favorite, but I didn’t recognize it for a few moments because I was reading it in Spanish. This scripture confirmed to me that Mexico City Temple is exactly where the Lord wanted me. It was Jacob 1:17: “Wherefore, I, Jacob, gave unto them these words as I taught them in the temple, having first obtained mine errand from the Lord.” The impact at this time of a scripture that was very familiar to me in English but not recognized immediately in Spanish was pretty strong and it humbled me considerably and brought a flow of tears and a feeling in my heart that this was indeed right. So, here I go. <br /><br />

