            <div id="restofstory4" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    This one particular time we were reporting to President Amado about our visit to the branches, and when we told how we were getting up to this particular branch, he got really upset and he told us we should never go up on that road, that we should go around the other way to get to that branch, because the particular road we had been traveling on had banditos everywhere. It was a very dangerous road. Even the people in Guatemala in that area didn’t go up on that road to get to that branch. <br /><br /> 

                    We said, “President, we’ve been going up there half a dozen times. We’re perfectly safe. We’re okay.” He said, “Don’t ever go up there again by that road. You take the other road and go around the other way.” We laughed. The President did not laugh; we kind of smiled a little bit, but we obeyed. The next time we went back, we took the other road, and we had to ford a stream to cross it, so we didn’t really enjoy it. If we had gone the other way we wouldn’t have had to cross that stream two times. The way we wanted to go we only had to cross it once.<br /><br /> 

                    One thing we learned while we were in Guatemala was that the Lord did watch over us. We had experiences where we could have been in danger, but because of choices that we made and the whisperings of the Spirit, we made the right choice, even if President Amado had to help us make that choice. <br /><br /> 

                    One other time that was kind of a humorous experience was when we were in Guatemala City. The guerillas were very active in that area. Guatemala City had a lot of distress. The presidential home had sandbags all around it, and there was military guarding the presidential home all of the time. As we traveled throughout the area, oftentimes when we would come closer into Guatemala City, we would be stopped by the police. They would pull us over to the side of the road, and we would have to get out of our car. They would inspect our car. They would look in the trunk and in the motor and everything to see if there was anything that we were doing wrong. That was something that happened quite often. <br /><br /> 

                    Later in the mission, they didn’t even stop us. If we stopped and rolled down the window, they’d ask us some questions. They could see that our Spanish was not very good. We told them we were missionaries, so they would just wave us on. One rather funny thing that happened one time was we were going out to a zone meeting with President Amado and one of his assistants. They were in the car ahead of us, and Elder Bird and I were following in our car. We came to one point in the road. The president’s car had been stopped by the military, and they were out of the car, he and the elder, and they were being inspected bodily, as well as their car. They practically took the car apart to see if there was anything in there that shouldn’t be. We pulled up and we could see what was happening. The policeman came over and we rolled down our window and we told him who we were. He said, “You just go on. No problemo. Just go ahead.” <br /><br /> 

                    When we got down to where we were having our zone meeting, I went to President Amado and I said, “Presidente, if you ever need any help in any difficulty, you just come to Elder Bird and I, and we will help you.”<br /><br /> 

                    We learned that we were watched over carefully. Our blessings were great down there. We had no fear, even though the military checked us time and time again. We had no fear at all. We felt totally safe. We knew we were being watched over. We had a wonderful experience in that mission. As I reflect back on those times, they’re some of my very choicest memories.
